# Linux Commands Cheat Sheet

## File System Commands

| Command | Usage                      |
| ------- | -------------------------- |
| pwd     | Show current directory     |
| ls      | List files and directories |
| ls -la  | Show detailed file listing |
| cd      | Change directory           |
| mkdir   | Create directory           |
| rmdir   | Remove empty directory     |
| touch   | Create empty file          |
| cp      | Copy files/directories     |
| mv      | Move or rename files       |
| rm      | Delete files               |
| find    | Search for files           |
| cat     | Display file content       |
| head    | Show first lines of a file |
| tail    | Show last lines of a file  |

## Process Management Commands

| Command     | Usage                        |
| ----------- | ---------------------------- |
| ps          | Display running processes    |
| ps -ef      | Show all running processes   |
| top         | Real-time process monitoring |
| htop        | Interactive process viewer   |
| kill PID    | Terminate a process          |
| kill -9 PID | Force kill a process         |
| pgrep       | Find process by name         |
| jobs        | Show background jobs         |
| bg          | Run job in background        |
| fg          | Bring job to foreground      |

## Networking Commands

| Command             | Usage                      |
| ------------------- | -------------------------- |
| ping google.com     | Check network connectivity |
| ip addr             | Show IP addresses          |
| curl URL            | Fetch data from URL        |
| wget URL            | Download files             |
| dig google.com      | DNS lookup                 |
| nslookup google.com | Query DNS records          |
| netstat -tulnp      | Show listening ports       |
| ss -tulnp           | Display socket statistics  |

## Disk & System Commands

| Command  | Usage                   |
| -------- | ----------------------- |
| df -h    | Show disk usage         |
| du -sh * | Show directory sizes    |
| free -h  | Display memory usage    |
| uname -a | Show system information |
| hostname | Display system hostname |

## Why These Commands Matter

* Inspect servers quickly
* Troubleshoot network issues
* Monitor processes and resources
* Manage files and logs
* Essential for Linux and DevOps work
